	<p>Yuen Yuen Ang is Assistant Professor in Political Science at the University of Michigan. She studies the role of government in economic development and bureaucratic politics in developing countries, focusing on contemporary China. Her research centers on how developing countries build good governance when their governments lack resources to implement conventional best practices. More specifically, she has studied unorthodox choices and innovations in the design of bureaucratic incentives, public pay structures, and public financial schemes in China, where she has conducted extensive fieldwork. She received the Andrew Mellon Foundation/American Council of Learned Societies (ACLS) Early Career Fellowships in two consecutive years, from 2008-2010. She received her doctoral degree in Political Science from Stanford University. Prior to joining Michigan, she was a faculty member at Columbia University School of International &amp; Public Affairs.</p>
